# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-blob-storage
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Object storage systems allow retention of massive amounts of unstructured data in which data is written once and read once (or many times).
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Object storage is used for purposes such as storing objects like videos and photos on Facebook, songs on Spotify, or files in online collaboration services, such as Dropbox.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] One of the limitations with object storage is that it is not intended for transactional data, as object storage was not designed to replace NAS file access and sharing; it does not support the locking and sharing mechanisms needed to maintain a single, accurately updated version of a file.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Jim Starkey coined the term ***blob*** working at Digital Equipment Corporation to refer to opaque data entities.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] The terminology was adopted for Rdb/VMS.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] *Blob* is often humorously explained to be an abbreviation for *binary large object*.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] According to Starkey, this backronym arose when Terry McKiever, working in marketing at Apollo Computer felt that the term needed to be an abbreviation.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] McKiever began using the expansion *basic large object*.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] This was later eclipsed by the retroactive explanation of blobs as *binary large objects*.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] According to Starkey, "Blob don't stand for nothin'." Rejecting the acronym, he explained his motivation behind the coinage, saying, "A blob is the thing that ate Cincinnatti [*sic*], Cleveland, or whatever", referring to the 1958 science fiction film *The Blob*.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] In 1995, research led by Garth Gibson on Network-Attached Secure Disks first promoted the concept of splitting less common operations, like namespace manipulations, from common operations, like reads and writes, to optimize the performance and scale of both.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] In the same year, a Belgian company – FilePool – was established to build the basis for archiving functions.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Object storage was proposed at Gibson's Carnegie Mellon University lab as a research project in 1996.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Another key concept was abstracting the writes and reads of data to more flexible data containers (objects).
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Fine grained access control through object storage architecture was further described by one of the NASD team, Howard Gobioff, who later was one of the inventors of the Google File System.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Other related work includes the Coda filesystem project at Carnegie Mellon, which started in 1987, and spawned the Lustre file system.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] There is also the OceanStore project at UC Berkeley, which started in 1999 and the Logistical Networking project at the University of Tennessee Knoxville, which started in 1998.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] In 1999, Gibson founded Panasas to commercialize the concepts developed by the NASD team.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Seagate Technology played a central role in the development of object storage.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] This paper was proposed to INCITS T-10 (International Committee for Information Technology Standards) with a goal to form a committee and design a specification based on the SCSI interface protocol.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] This defined objects as abstracted data, with unique identifiers and metadata, how objects related to file systems, along with many other innovative concepts.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Anderson presented many of these ideas at the SNIA conference in October 1999.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] The presentation revealed an IP Agreement that had been signed in February 1997 between the original collaborators (with Seagate represented by Anderson and Chris Malakapalli) and covered the benefits of object storage, scalable computing, platform independence, and storage management.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] One of the design principles of object storage is to abstract some of the lower layers of storage away from the administrators and applications.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Thus, data is exposed and managed as objects instead of blocks or (exclusively) files.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Objects contain additional descriptive properties which can be used for better indexing or management.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Administrators do not have to perform lower-level storage functions like constructing and managing logical volumes to utilize disk capacity or setting RAID levels to deal with disk failure.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Object storage also allows the addressing and identification of individual objects by more than just file name and file path.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Object storage adds a unique identifier within a bucket, or across the entire system, to support much larger namespaces and eliminate name collisions.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Object storage explicitly separates file metadata from data to support additional capabilities.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Object storage provides programmatic interfaces to allow applications to manipulate data.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] At the base level, this includes Create, read, update and delete (CRUD) functions for basic read, write and delete operations.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Some object storage implementations go further, supporting additional functionality like object/file versioning, object replication, life-cycle management and movement of objects between different tiers and types of storage.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Most API implementations are REST-based, allowing the use of many standard HTTP calls.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] The vast majority of cloud storage available in the market leverages an object-storage architecture.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Some notable examples are Amazon S3, which debuted in March 2006, Microsoft Azure Blob Storage, IBM Cloud Object Storage, Rackspace Cloud Files (whose code was donated in 2010 to Openstack project and released as OpenStack Swift), and Google Cloud Storage released in May 2010.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Some distributed file systems use an object-based architecture, where file metadata is stored in metadata servers and file data is stored in object storage servers.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] File system client software interacts with the distinct servers, and abstracts them to present a full file system to users and applications.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Some early incarnations of object storage were used for archiving, as implementations were optimized for data services like immutability, not performance.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] EMC Centera and Hitachi HCP (formerly known as HCAP) are two commonly cited object storage products for archiving.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Another example is Quantum ActiveScale Object Storage Platform.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] More general-purpose object-storage systems came to market around 2008.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] A few object-storage systems support Unified File and Object storage, allowing clients to store objects on a storage system while simultaneously other clients store files on the same storage system.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Other vendors in the area of Hybrid cloud storage are using Cloud storage gateways to provide a file access layer over object storage, implementing file access protocols such as SMB and NFS.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Some large Internet companies developed their own software when object-storage products were not commercially available or use cases were very specific.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Facebook famously invented their own object-storage software, code-named Haystack, to address their particular massive-scale photo management needs efficiently.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Object storage at the protocol and device layer was proposed 20 years ago and approved for the SCSI command set nearly 10 years ago as "Object-based Storage Device Commands" (OSD), however, it had not been put into production until the development of the Seagate Kinetic Open Storage platform.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] The SCSI command set for Object Storage Devices was developed by a working group of the SNIA for the T10 committee of the International Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS).
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] T10 is responsible for all SCSI standards.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] One of the first object-storage products, Lustre, is used in 70% of the Top 100 supercomputers and ~50% of the Top 500.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] As of June 16, 2013, this includes 7 of the top 10, including the current fourth fastest system on the list - China's Tianhe-2 and the seventh fastest, the Titan supercomputer at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Object-storage systems had good adoption in the early 2000s as an archive platform, particularly in the wake of compliance laws like Sarbanes-Oxley.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] After five years in the market, EMC's Centera product claimed over 3,500 customers and 150 petabytes shipped by 2007.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Hitachi's HCP product also claims many petabyte-scale customers.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Newer object storage systems have also gotten some traction, particularly around very large custom applications like eBay's auction site, where EMC Atmos is used to manage over 500 million objects a day.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] As of March 3, 2014, EMC claims to have sold over 1.5 exabytes of Atmos storage.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] On July 1, 2014, Los Alamos National Lab chose the Scality RING as the basis for a 500-petabyte storage environment, which would be among the largest ever.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] "Captive" object storage systems like Facebook's Haystack have scaled impressively.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] In April 2009, Haystack was managing 60 billion photos and 1.5 petabytes of storage, adding 220 million photos and 25 terabytes a week.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Facebook more recently stated that they were adding 350 million photos a day and were storing 240 billion photos.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] This could equal as much as 357 petabytes.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Cloud storage has become pervasive as many new web and mobile applications choose it as a common way to store binary data.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] As the storage back-end to many popular applications like Smugmug and Dropbox, Amazon S3 has grown to massive scale, citing over 2-trillion objects stored in April 2013.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Two months later, Microsoft claimed that they stored even more objects in Azure at 8.5 trillion.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] By April 2014, Azure claimed over 20-trillion objects stored.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Windows Azure Storage manages Blobs (user files), Tables (structured storage), and Queues (message delivery) and counts them all as objects.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Coldago Research adopted qualitative and quantitative analysis of the object storage market to rank 13 notable vendors based on technological capabilities, market momentum, and innovation trajectory.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] The 2024 Coldago object storage market leader rating is in alphabetical order: Cloudian, DataCore, Dell EMC, Huawei, IBM, MinIO, Pure Storage, Quantum, and VAST Data.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] In the first version of the OSD standard, objects are specified with a 64-bit partition ID and a 64-bit object ID.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Partitions are created and deleted within an OSD, and objects are created and deleted within partitions.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] There are no fixed sizes associated with partitions or objects; they are allowed to grow subject to physical size limitations of the device or logical quota constraints on a partition.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] An extensible set of attributes describe objects.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Some attributes are implemented directly by the OSD, such as the number of bytes in an object and the modification time of an object.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] There is a special policy tag attribute that is part of the security mechanism.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Other attributes are uninterpreted by the OSD.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] These are set on objects by the higher-level storage systems that use the OSD for persistent storage.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] For example, attributes might be used to classify objects, or to capture relationships among different objects stored on different OSDs.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] A list command returns a list of identifiers for objects within a partition, optionally filtered by matches against their attribute values.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] A list command can also return selected attributes of the listed objects.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Read and write commands can be combined, or piggy-backed, with commands to get and set attributes.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] This ability reduces the number of times a high-level storage system has to cross the interface to the OSD, which can improve overall efficiency.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] A second generation of the SCSI command set, "Object-Based Storage Devices - 2" (OSD-2) added support for snapshots, collections of objects, and improved error handling.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] A snapshot is a point-in-time copy of all the objects in a partition into a new partition.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] The OSD can implement a space-efficient copy using copy-on-write techniques so that the two partitions share objects that are unchanged between the snapshots, or the OSD might physically copy the data to the new partition.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] The standard defines clones, which are writeable, and snapshots, which are read-only.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] A collection is a special kind of object that contains the identifiers of other objects.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] There are operations to add and delete from collections, and there are operations to get or set attributes for all the objects in a collection.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Collections are also used for error reporting.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] If an object becomes damaged by the occurrence of a media defect (i.e., a bad spot on the disk) or by a software error within the OSD implementation, its identifier is put into a special error collection.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] The higher-level storage system that uses the OSD can query this collection and take corrective action as necessary.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] The border between an object store and a key–value store is blurred, with key–value stores being sometimes loosely referred to as object stores.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] A traditional block storage interface uses a series of fixed size blocks which are numbered starting at 0.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Data must be that exact fixed size and can be stored in a particular block which is identified by its logical block number (LBN).
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Later, one can retrieve that block of data by specifying its unique LBN.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] With a key–value store, data is identified by a key rather than a LBN.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] A key might be "cat" or "olive" or "42".
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] It can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Data (called a value in this parlance) does not need to be a fixed size and also can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] One stores data by presenting the key and data (value) to the data store and can later retrieve the data by presenting the key.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] This concept is seen in programming languages.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Python calls them dictionaries, Perl calls them hashes, Java, Rust and C++ call them maps, etc.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Several data stores also implement key–value stores such as Memcached, Redis and CouchDB.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Object stores are similar to key–value stores in two respects.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] First, the object identifier or URL (the equivalent of the key) can be an arbitrary string.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Second, data may be of an arbitrary size.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] There are, however, a few key differences between key–value stores and object stores.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] First, object stores also allow one to associate a limited set of attributes (metadata) with each piece of data.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] The combination of a key, value, and set of attributes is referred to as an object.
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Second, object stores are optimized for large amounts of data (hundreds of megabytes or even gigabytes), whereas for key–value stores the value is expected to be relatively small (kilobytes).
[src:azure-blob-storage/binary-large-object] Finally, object stores usually offer weaker consistency guarantees such as eventual consistency, whereas key–value stores offer strong consistency.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services may be accessed through a colocated cloud computing service, a web service application programming interface (API) or by applications that use the API, such as cloud desktop storage, a cloud storage gateway or Web-based content management systems.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud computing is believed to have been invented by J.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Licklider in the 1960s with his work on ARPANET to connect people and data from anywhere at any time.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] In 1983, CompuServe offered its consumer users a small amount of disk space that could be used to store any files they chose to upload.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] In 1994, AT&T launched PersonaLink Services, an online platform for personal and business communication and entrepreneurship.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] In 2005, Box announced an online file sharing and personal cloud content management service for businesses.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Alibaba Cloud was launched in September 2009, three years after AWS.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] As of 2024, Gartner ranked cloud storage platforms as follows: AWS, Google, Microsoft, Oracle, Alibaba, IBM, Huawei and Tencent.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] These account for 97% of the global cloud services market.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] This rating was based on ability to execute in market and innovation vision.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] In 2023, 80% of China's technology companies and half of AI LLM companies ran on Alibaba Cloud while in the US dominance belonged to AWS with 31 to 50% share.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] In 2026, Alibaba is scheduled to spend more than 300 million yuan, about $52 billion, on artificial intelligence and cloud infrastructure over the next three years, a figure much larger than the amount spent the previous year.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Data centers will also be expanding, and AI models like Qwen.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Alibaba's CEO, Eddie Wu, describes the amount spent as the largest to date on cloud and AI.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Also, he explained that they expect much of the internal AI workload to run on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Spending will include specific items such as GPU-like accelerators and large-scale data centers to support internal workloads and external client functions, underscoring Alibaba's pivot from e-commerce to cloud infrastructure.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is based on highly virtualized infrastructure and is like broader cloud computing in terms of interfaces, near-instant elasticity and scalability, multi-tenancy, and metered resources.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services can be used from an off-premises service (Amazon S3) or deployed on-premises (ViON Capacity Services).
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] There are three types of cloud storage: a hosted object storage service, file storage, and block storage.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Each of these cloud storage types offer their own unique advantages.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Security of stored data and data in transit may be a concern when storing sensitive data at a cloud storage provider.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Outsourcing data storage increases the attack surface area.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is a rich resource for both hackers and national security agencies.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Because the cloud holds data from many different users and organizations, hackers see it as a very valuable target.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] The number of people with access to the data who could be compromised (e.g., bribed, or coerced) increases dramatically.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Decryption keys that are kept by the service user, as opposed to the service provider, limit access to data by service provider employees.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] As for sharing multiple data in the cloud with multiple users, a large number of keys has to be distributed to users via secure channels for decryption, also it has to be securely stored and managed by the users in their devices.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Storing these keys requires rather expensive secure storage.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] To overcome that, key-aggregate cryptosystem can be used.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] It increases the number of networks over which the data travels.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Instead of just a local area network (LAN) or storage area network (SAN), data stored on a cloud requires a WAN (wide area network) to connect them both.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] By sharing storage and networks with many other users/customers it is possible for other customers to access your data.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Sometimes because of erroneous actions, faulty equipment, a bug and sometimes because of criminal intent.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] This risk applies to all types of storage and not only cloud storage.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] The risk of having data read during transmission can be mitigated through encryption technology.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Encryption in transit protects data as it is being transmitted to and from the cloud service.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Encryption at rest protects data that is stored at the service provider.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Encrypting data in an on-premises cloud service on-ramp system can provide both kinds of encryption protection.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] There are several options available to avoid security issues.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] One option is to use a private cloud instead of a public cloud.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Another option is to ingest data in an encrypted format where the key is held within the on-premise infrastructure.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] To this end, access is often by use of on-premise cloud storage gateways that have options to encrypt the data prior to transfer.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Typically, cloud storage Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by other services offered within the same provider.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, service providers typically do not offer monetary compensation.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage is a term for a storage infrastructure that uses a combination of on-premises storage resources with cloud storage.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] The on-premises storage is usually managed by the organization, while the public cloud storage provider is responsible for the management and security of the data stored in the cloud.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be implemented by an on-premises cloud storage gateway that presents a file system or object storage interface that users can access in the same way they would access a local storage system.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] The cloud storage gateway transparently transfers the data to and from the cloud storage service, providing low latency access to the data through a local cache.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be used to supplement an organization's internal storage resources, or it can be used as the primary storage infrastructure.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] In either case, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater flexibility and scalability than traditional on-premises storage infrastructure.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] There are several benefits to using hybrid cloud storage, including the ability to cache frequently used data on-site for quick access, while inactive cold data is stored off-site in the cloud.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] This can save space, reduce storage costs and improve performance.
[src:azure-blob-storage/cloud-storage] Additionally, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater redundancy and fault tolerance, as data is stored in both on-premises and cloud storage infrastructure.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:azure-blob-storage/data-lake] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] In object-oriented (OO) and functional programming, an **immutable object** (unchangeable object) is an object whose state cannot be modified after it is created.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] This is in contrast to a **mutable object** (changeable object), which can be modified after it is created.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] In some cases, an object is considered immutable even if some internally used attributes change, but the object's state appears unchanging from an external point of view.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] For example, an object that uses memoization to cache the results of expensive computations could still be considered an immutable object.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Strings and other concrete objects are typically expressed as immutable objects to improve readability and runtime efficiency in object-oriented programming.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Immutable objects are also useful because they are inherently thread-safe.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Other benefits are that they are simpler to understand and reason about and offer higher security than mutable objects.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] In imperative programming, values held in program variables whose content never changes are known as *constants* to differentiate them from variables that could be altered during execution.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Examples include conversion factors from meters to feet, or the value of pi to several decimal places.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Read-only fields may be calculated when the program runs (unlike constants, which are known beforehand), but never change after they are initialized.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Sometimes, one talks of certain *fields* of an object being immutable.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] This means that there is no way to change those parts of the object state, even though other parts of the object may be changeable (*weakly immutable*).
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] If all fields are immutable, then the object is immutable.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] If the whole object cannot be extended by another class, the object is called *strongly immutable*.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] This might, for example, help to explicitly enforce certain invariants about certain data in the object staying the same through the lifetime of the object.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] In some languages, this is done with a keyword (e.g.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] `const` in C++, `final` in Java) that designates the field as immutable.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Some languages reverse it: in OCaml, fields of an object or record are by default immutable, and must be explicitly marked with `mutable` to be so.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] In most object-oriented languages, objects can be referred to using references.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Some examples of such languages are Java, C++, C#, VB.NET, and many scripting languages, such as Perl, Python, and Ruby.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] In this case, it matters whether the state of an object can vary when objects are shared via references.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] If an object is known to be immutable, it is preferred to create a reference of it instead of copying the entire object.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] This is done to conserve memory by preventing data duplication and avoid calls to constructors and destructors; it also results in a potential boost in execution speed.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] The reference copying technique is much more difficult to use for mutable objects, because if any user of a mutable object reference changes it, all other users of that reference see the change.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] If this is not the intended effect, it can be difficult to notify the other users to have them respond correctly.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] In these situations, defensive copying of the entire object rather than the reference is usually an easy but costly solution.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] The observer pattern is an alternative technique for handling changes to mutable objects.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] A technique that blends the advantages of **mutable** and **immutable** objects, and is supported directly in almost all modern hardware, is copy-on-write (COW).
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Using this technique, when a user asks the system to copy an object, it instead merely creates a new reference that still points to the same object.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] As soon as a user attempts to modify the object through a particular reference, the system makes a real copy, applies the modification to that, and sets the reference to refer to the new copy.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] The other users are unaffected, because they still refer to the original object.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Therefore, under COW, all users appear to have a mutable version of their objects, although in the case that users do not modify their objects, the space-saving and speed advantages of immutable objects are preserved.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Copy-on-write is popular in virtual memory systems because it allows them to save memory space while still correctly handling anything an application program might do.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] The practice of always using references in place of copies of equal objects is known as *interning*.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] If interning is used, two objects are considered equal if and only if their references, typically represented as pointers or integers, are equal.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Some languages do this automatically: for example, Python automatically interns short strings.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] If the algorithm that implements interning is guaranteed to do so in every case that it is possible, then comparing objects for equality is reduced to comparing their pointers – a substantial gain in speed in most applications.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] (Even if the algorithm is not guaranteed to be comprehensive, there still exists the possibility of a fast path case improvement when the objects are equal and use the same reference.) Interning is generally only useful for immutable objects.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Immutable objects can be useful in multi-threaded applications.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Multiple threads can act on data represented by immutable objects without concern of the data being changed by other threads.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Immutable objects are therefore considered more *thread-safe* than mutable objects.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Immutability does not imply that the object as stored in the computer's memory is unwriteable.
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] Rather, immutability is a compile-time construct that indicates what a programmer can do through the normal interface of the object, not necessarily what they can absolutely do (for instance, by circumventing the type system or violating const correctness in C or C++).
[src:azure-blob-storage/immutable-object] In Python, Java and the .NET Framework, strings are immutable objects.
