[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Azure was first introduced at the Professional Developers Conference (PDC) in October 2008 under the code name "Project Red Dog".
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] It was officially launched as Windows Azure in February 2010 and later renamed to Microsoft Azure on March 25, 2014.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure uses large-scale virtualization at Microsoft data centers worldwide and offers more than 600 services.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure offers a service level agreement (SLA) that guarantees 99.9% availability for applications and data hosted on its platform, subject to specific terms and conditions outlined in the SLA documentation.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] The Microsoft Azure Service Bus allows applications running on Azure premises or off-premises devices to communicate with Azure.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] This helps to build scalable and reliable applications in a service-oriented architecture (SOA).
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] A PaaS offering that can be used for encoding, content protection, streaming, or analytics.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Azure has a worldwide content delivery network (CDN) designed to efficiently deliver audio, video, applications, images, and other static files.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] It improves the performance of websites by caching static files closer to users, based on their geographic location.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Users can manage the network using a REST-based HTTP API.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Azure has 118 point-of-presence locations across 100 cities worldwide (also known as Edge locations) as of January 2023.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Through Azure Blockchain Workbench, Microsoft is providing the required infrastructure to set up a consortium network in multiple topologies using a variety of consensus mechanisms.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Microsoft provides integration from these blockchain platforms to other Microsoft services to streamline the development of distributed applications.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Microsoft supports many general-purpose blockchains, including Ethereum and Hyperledger Fabric and purpose-built blockchains like Corda.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Azure functions are used in serverless computing architectures, where subscribers can execute code as an event-driven Function-as-a-Service (FaaS) without managing the underlying server resources.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Customers using Azure functions are billed based on per-second resource consumption and executions.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Azure Local (previously Azure Stack HCI) is a hyper-converged infrastructure (HCI) product that uses validated hardware to run virtualized workloads on-premises to consolidate aging infrastructure and connect to Azure for cloud services.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Launched in September 2020, Azure Orbital lets private industries and government agencies process satellite data quickly by connecting directly to cloud computing networks.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Mobile cloud computing ground stations are also available to provide connectivity to remote locations without ground infrastructure.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Third-party satellite systems, like SpaceX's Starlink and SES' O3b constellation, can be employed.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] SES plans to use Microsoft's data centers to provide cloud connectivity to remote areas through its next generation O3b mPOWER MEO satellites alongside Microsoft's data centers.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] The company will deploy satellite control and uplink ground stations to achieve this.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] SES launched the first two O3b mPOWER satellites in December 2022; nine more are scheduled between 2023 and 2024.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] According to Microsoft, satellite cloud connectivity can provide lower latency than terrestrial fiber routes in specific regions.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] The company stated that during network testing for Xbox Cloud, satellite connections out-performed terrestrial networks in certain rural or geographically remote areas of the United States due to fewer network routing hops.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Azure Orbital was retired in December 2024, with existing assets being sold off to Space Leasing International.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In August 2024, Azure launched Azure Container Storage, a platform-managed container-native storage service for the public cloud.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] The service supports Ephemeral Disks (Local NVMe/Temp SSD) and Azure Disks for containerized applications.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Azure Quantum provides access to quantum hardware and software.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] The platform provides access to third-party quantum systems utilizing varied hardware architectures, including trapped ion, neutral atom, and superconducting systems.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In 2021, Microsoft developed the quantum programming language Q# (pronounced Q Sharp) and an open-source quantum development kit for algorithm development and simulation.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In 2023, Microsoft developed Quantum Intermediate Representation (QIR) from LLVM as a common interface between programming languages and target quantum processors.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] The Azure Quantum Resource Estimator estimates the resources required to execute a given quantum algorithm on a fault-tolerant quantum computer.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] It can also show how future quantum computers will impact today's encryption algorithms.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] As of 2018, Azure was available in 54 regions, and Microsoft was the first primary cloud provider to establish facilities in Africa, with two regions in South Africa.
