[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] It also integrates with Microsoft Visual Studio, Git, and Eclipse.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Users can manage Azure services in multiple ways, one of which is through the Web-based Azure Portal, which became generally available in December 2015.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Apart from accessing services via API, users can browse active resources, adjust settings, launch new resources, and view primary monitoring data of functional virtual machines and services using the portal.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Regarding cloud resources, Microsoft Azure offers two deployment models: the "classic" model and the Azure Resource Manager.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In the classic model, each resource, like a virtual machine or SQL database, had to be managed separately, but in 2014, Azure introduced the Azure Resource Manager, which allows users to group related services.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] This update makes it easier and more efficient to deploy, manage, and monitor resources that work closely together.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] The classic model will eventually be phased out.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In January 2025, Microsoft announced plans to invest $80 billion in AI and data centers as part of its fiscal year 2025 budget.
