[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In 2025, an activist campaign named "No Azure for Apartheid" accused Microsoft of providing cloud and AI services to entities involved in Israeli policies within the Palestinian territories.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Campaign organizers argue that Azure's technology could enable surveillance and displacement, drawing parallels to historical corporate involvement in apartheid regimes.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Similar activism has targeted other technology companies, such as the No Tech for Apartheid movement directed at Google and Amazon, though critics state that Microsoft's specific government contracts and military partnerships draw heightened scrutiny.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Protesters have demanded transparency, ethical oversight, and the termination of contracts that they state facilitate human rights violations.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Microsoft has stated that its operations comply with international laws and regulations.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] The following is a list of Microsoft Azure outages and service disruptions.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] A large variety of Azure certifications can be attained, each requiring one or multiple successfully completed examinations.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Certification levels range from beginner, intermediate to expert.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Microsoft Azure's services can have varied and complex pricing models.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In August 2021, researchers from Wiz Research claimed to have discovered a vulnerability in the Azure Cosmos DB database, referred to as "ChaosDB." They claimed that they had gained complete unrestricted access to the accounts and databases of several thousand Microsoft Azure customers.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In August 2021, Microsoft claimed they mitigated the vulnerability and no customer data was accessed.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In September 2021, researchers from Palo Alto Networks claimed to discover a significant cross-account takeover vulnerability in Azure Container Instances, named "Azurescape".
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] According to Palo Alto Networks' researchers, this vulnerability is the first known instance that allows one user of a public cloud service to escape their environment and execute code on other users' environments within the same service.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] Although Microsoft quickly patched the issue, Palo Alto Networks advised Azure customers to revoke any privileged credentials deployed before August 31, 2021, as a precaution.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In September 2021, Microsoft claimed they fixed the vulnerability.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In September 2021, researchers from Wiz Research claimed they found four critical vulnerabilities in the Open Management Infrastructure (OMI), which is Azure's software agent deployed on a large portion of Linux VMs in Azure.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] The researchers named it "OMIGOD" and claimed that these vulnerabilities allowed for remote code execution within the Azure network and could escalate privileges to root.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] They claimed that the vulnerabilities affected various Azure services, including Azure Log Analytics, Azure Diagnostics, and Azure Security Center.
[src:azure-blob-storage/microsoft-azure] In response, Microsoft announced that it had released fixes for the aforementioned vulnerabilities in September 2021.
